entry.title: [RWS] Tidy up RWS-serialization
entry.content:
This makes a few mechanical changes:

* Uses a `const char*` instead of `std::string`, since all the site_type

strings are known statically.

* Uses a `std::map` instead of

`base::Value::Dict`, for clarity (since the map doesn't need to be a

`base::Value`; it just needs to allow lookups by primary).

* Avoids using deprecated JSONWriter::WriteWithOptions method.

* Avoids copying sets values in for loop.

* Uses operator[] and EnsureList to avoid manually inserting dicts and

lists, and avoid duplicate map/dict lookups.

* Checks return value of JSON serialization.

* Removes caching of serialized output, since the RWSSource instance

is deleted after each individual request anyway and the cache is not

used. (Furthermore, this caching didn't take service initialization

or preference changes into account, so even if it had had any

effect, the cache would have yielded stale values if the UI was

opened before/after a preference change or during browser startup.)

* Makes PopulateRelatedWebsiteSetsInfo into a stateless function in an

anonymous namespace.

entry.title: [ios] Show IPH for share button after copying from omnibox occurs.
entry.content:
Data flow: OmniboxViewIOS (detects the copy event, sends the toolbar

command) -> `OmniboxCoordinator` (handles the toolbar command, waits for

the omnibox de-focus done, sends the help commands) -> `BubblePresenter`

(handles the help commands, show the IPH)



The reason having to go through `OmniboxCoordinator` as an

intermediator is the display of IPH will be anchored to a slightly off location if triggered before the location bar is settled, I assume it's

because of the views are still moving.



An alternative that is a more direct call from `OmniboxViewIOS` to

`BubblePresenter` is to send the help command after an arbitrary delay of 1s when user dismisses the omnibox, but that's less predictable.

entry.title: Shared Storage: Allow iframe header writes if permission on redirect
entry.content:
We correct the behavior of writing to shared storage from response

headers to match the spec with regard to how `PermissionsPolicy`

checks are handled.



Currently, if permission is revoked for any request in a redirect

chain, then no subsequent request in that chain can write to shared

storage from response headers.



This CL updates the behavior for `HTMLIframeElement` so that, for

redirect chains of requests that have opted-in via

`sharedStorageWritable`, each request in the chain has its

`PermissionsPolicy` checked independently of the others in the chain.



https://crrev.com/c/4911530 will do the same for `fetch()` and

`HTMLImageElement`, and fixes the network service code common to all

three.

entry.title: Throttling: throttling of undrawn frame
entry.content:
Previous implementation throttles browser processes (Lacros incl.) to a

hardcoded 20fps rate. There is some extra logic supposed to enable more

aggressive throttling (hardcoded as well because...) if the frame aren't

drawn. However for that throttle to kick in we would need an absence of

frame timing, with RFS that would mean no compositor frame have been

committed and yet we are considering a new begin frame.

The proposed change here, enables the more aggressive throttling of

undrawn frame even when frame timing details are availablei but no frame

has been drawn which should mean failed presentation.

Ensuring failed presentation should also limit the impact on

core-web-vitals and metric measurements.

entry.title: Shared Storage: Allow fetch/img header writes if permission on redirect
entry.content:
We correct the behavior of writing to shared storage from response

headers to match the spec with regard to how `PermissionsPolicy`

checks are handled.



Currently, if permission is revoked for any request in a redirect

chain, then no subsequent request in that chain can write to shared

storage from response headers.



This CL updates the behavior for `fetch()` and `HTMLImageElement` so

that, for redirect chains of requests that have opted-in via

`sharedStorageWritable`, each request in the chain has its

`PermissionsPolicy` checked independently of the others in the chain.



https://crrev.com/c/4935951 will do the same for `HTMLIframeElement`.

Android will silently ignore any invalid style references, instead of

crashing/failing like it usually does when things do not resolve

correctly. As a result of this, we've seen multiple times where a

known style attributes, and makes sure they seem well formatted.

Invalid style names will not be caught, only straight forward syntax

mistakes.

entry.title: Define supervised user extensions permissions feature for Desktop platforms only.
entry.content:
The extensions permissions feature for supervised users is part of the feature set to enable parental controls on Linux, Mac, and Windows platforms. The behavior of this feature will be adapted in the coming months and removed from the experiment feature set we are building for launch/4230258 due to recent issues in the experiment ramp-up (crbug/1493374, b/301588664).

entry.content:

locally.

This CL increases log verbosity in TestDohServer, which will hopefully

give us a hint as to where these martian queries are coming from.

entry.content:

should be eligible for IP Protection because this value will be

populated with an iframe origin or empty in the case of Fenced

Frames and opaque origins. By plumbing through the NAK, the

MDL-derived URL matchers will have more context about the request

and whether it is in a third party context.



Changing the URL matcher behavior will be done in a follow-up CL.
